        <span role="byline">Sources: NA&#xAD;TIONAL UNIVERSIT Y OF SIN&#xAD;GA&#xAD;PORE, SOUTH JAVA DEEP SEA BIODIVERSI&#xAD;T Y EX&#xAD;PE&#xAD;DI&#xAD;TION (SJADES)&#xD;&#xA;PHO&#xAD;TOS: SJADES STRAITS TIMES GRAPH&#xAD;ICS</span>
        <p data-role="text">&#x2022; Good things come to those that wait. The tri&#xAD;pod fish is known to lie in wait for prey on the seabed, propped up by its tail and fins.&#xD;&#xA;&#x2022; Other crea&#xAD;tures have de&#xAD;vel&#xAD;oped long feel&#xAD;ers that can help them make their way around in the dark and de&#xAD;tect prey. &#x2022; But other or&#xAD;gan&#xAD;isms have adapted by hav&#xAD;ing larger eyes that can cap&#xAD;ture any in&#xAD;com&#xAD;ing re&#xAD;flec&#xAD;tion. &#x2022; Some species make their own shells, which are of&#xAD;ten as thin as pa&#xAD;per. &#x2022; Oth&#xAD;ers make use of the things around them, such as sea anemones. &#x2022; This crab made its home in a sunken piece of wood. Tri&#xAD;pod fish Fang&#xAD;tooth Chloroph&#xAD;thal&#xAD;mus corniger Ju&#xAD;ve&#xAD;nile glass eel</p>
